# Greetings 

This a simple application to greet. The application can be built and run to greet 
either CSCI 160 or CSCI 161. The application says Hello! and Goodbye! either to 
CSCI 160 or to CSCI 161. 


## Technologies

This application has been developed using C++ programming language. This application
can be built and run on a system with a GCC compiler. Unix make utility is necessary
to build as well as to run the unit test of this application. 

To perform unit test of this application GCC compiler must have Boost Unit Test 
Library installed. This application has been tested on Debian 4.9 (Linux) with 
GCC 6.3.0 and BOOST 1.62. 



## Build and Installation


To build this application from the source code enter following command from the root directory 
of this application.

	>make

To clean the files from the previous build of the application enter following command from the
root directory of the application.

	>make clean

There is no installation script to install this application automatically. However, you can manually
install this application by copying the executable file (either 'greetingcsci160' or 'greetingcsci161') 
from the 'bin' subdirectory of this application to a system directory, for example, '/usr/local/bin', 
that is listed in the '$PATH' environment variable of your system. You need system privileges in order
to copy the executable into your target directory.




## Usage

You can run both 'greetingcsci160' and 'greetingcsci161' executables of this application one after
another from the root directory of this application by entring following command.

	>make run

You can run only 'greetingcsci160' executable of this application from the root directory of this 
application by entring following command.

	>make run-greeting-csci160

You can run only 'greetingcsci161' executable of this application from the root directory of this 
application by entring following command.

	>make run-greeting-csci161

You can run both 'testgreetingcsci160' and 'testgreetingcsci161' unit tests of this application one 
after another from the root directory of this application by entring following command.

	>make test

You can run 'testgreetingcsci160' unit test of this application from the root directory of this 
application by entring following command.

	>make test-greeting-csci160


You can run 'testgreetingcsci161' unit test of this application from the root directory of this 
application by entring following command.

	>make test-greeting-csci161

If you have manually installed 'greetingcsci160' by copying 'bin/greetingcsci160' executable
file in your system directory, for example, in '/usr/local/bin', which is listed in your '$PATH' 
environment variable, you can run 'greetingcsci160' from any other directory in your system by 
simply entering 'greetingcsci160' on the command prompt as follows:

	>greetingcsci160

If you have manually installed 'greetingcsci161' by copying 'bin/greetingcsci161' executable
file in your system directory, for example, in '/usr/local/bin', which is listed in your '$PATH' 
environment variable, you can run 'greetingcsci161' from any other directory in your system by 
simply entering 'greetingcsci161' on the command prompt as follows:

	>greetingcsci161



